Run TestCatalogServiceApplication and do "docker ps" to see the postgres image running
then go to: http://localhost:8081/actuator, to see the actuator endpoints
then go to the application.yml in catalog-service to expose all the end points of actuator with "management:endpoints:web:exposure:include: *"
Add this two to catalog-service pom.xml "<goal>build-info</goal> & <plugin><groupId>pl.project13.maven</groupId><artifactId>git-commit-id-plugin</artifactId></plugin>"
In the sidebar, click maven and run the package folder to see git.properties
in the application.yml, add   Management:info:git: mode: full
then go to http://localhost:8081/actuator/info to see the git information in git.properties file
    -Configure code formatting, swagger
go to https://springdoc.org/
For the integration between spring-boot and swagger-ui, add the library to the list of your project dependencies (No additional configuration is needed).
"   <dependency>
       <groupId>org.springdoc</groupId>
       <artifactId>springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui</artifactId>
       <version>2.8.17</version>
    </dependency>
"
The Swagger UI page will then be available at http://localhost:8081/swagger-ui.html
and the OpenAPI description will be available at the following url for json format: http://localhost:8081/v3/api-docs
    Formatting
The spotless plugin checks weda the code is properly formatted, and it allows the use of different formatters to format our code.
if the code is not formatted, the build will fail, the solution is to
Open the Maven tool window (usually on the right side).
Expand your project.
Expand Plugins.
Expand spotless.
Double-click spotless:apply.
rebuild the project and you will see no errors
or
run ./mvnw spotless:apply
you can also do ls to see if mvnw is available.
IntelliJ will run it using its bundled Maven.

    -Setup Docker Compose for Local Development:
create a deployment directory inside the parent directory.
create a docker-compose directory in the deployment.
create an infra.yml file inside docker-compose directory.
define the database properties in the application.yml of catalog-service.
then we should be able to start the catalog service.
in the terminal, we cd into deployment/docker-compose container
then we run "docker-compose -f infra.yml up -d"
to start the catalog-service container on docker
we view the running container using Portainer
    Portainer(optional)
Docker is the engine that actually creates and runs containers.
Portainer is just a graphical dashboard for Docker.
that is docker commands in ui form
eg "docker ps": show me only running containers but in Portainer we just see the containers with the tag running.
More docker commands
docker ps -a: Show all containers.
docker images: Show downloaded images.
docker logs <container-name>: Show a container's logs.
docker stop <container-name>: Stop a running container.
docker start <container-name>: Start a stopped container.

Run CatalogServiceApplication and test the end points

    -Setup Cl using Github actions
In Github actions, When you commit your code, you can trigger build and define what you want to do within the build.
create a github folder inside the parent element,
create a workflows folder inside the github folder
create a catalog-service.yml
This catalog-service.yml will only run when changes are made to the catalog-service..
so from our root project, we should be able to run "./mvnw -ntp verify" in the terminal, it is used to verify if our code is healthy after building.
now we can commit our code
improvement
if our code is not perfectly formatted, the build will fail
and if run "./mvnw -ntp verify" to check if everything is okay
i.e sometimes we have to do multiple steps before we push the code
sometimes we cannot remember all the steps or we are too lazy to do them,
we use a utility/tool called Taskfile.dev and when we run it, it will execute all the steps we have given it to do for us.
How to use Task
-install it "winget install Task.Task" since i already have winget on my system
-run task --version to see if it has installed.
create a Taskfile.yml file
then run task on the terminal to run general command
more commands
task start_infra
task stop_infra

    Todo 3
-Code Organization: Package by layer vs Feature
Usual standard
Controller -> Service -> Repository -> DB
    Package By Layer                    Package By Feature
root                                    root
    -Controllers                            -products
        -ProductControllers                     -ProductController
        -CustomerController                     -ProductService
    -Services                                   -ProductRepository
        -ProductService                      -Customers
        -CustomersService                       -CustomerController
    -repositories                               -CustomerService
        -ProductRepository                      -CustomerRepository
        -CustomerRepository

-Implement Get Products API with Pagination
*Create flyway migration scripts for creating products table and populating books data.
We use flyway for database migration and we are going to create migration script in catalog-service/resources/db/migration V1__create_products_table.sql
and static books data in V2__add_books_data.sql
this is the naming convention for flyway migration.
we use task start_infra to automatically start the database using docker compose.
run the CatalogServiceApplication
open DBeaver and check for the flyway_schema_history.
note:once a script is applied, do not make changes.
if you want to make changes, you will have to add another migration script.

*Implement Get/api/products?page=1 Get all products
create ProductController class inside web/controller folder
and the request is going to accept a page request parameter
Service layer is annotated with @Transactional and it is considered as transactional boundary.
That is you invoke a database transaction anytime you invoke a service method.
create productEntity, productController, productRepository, productService
whenever you are using pagination, always apply how to sort.
We should not be exposing our entities to the front end.
we dont need to make ProductController public cos nobody is accessing it, it is just being called from the url.
The only classes we make public are the ones that are shared across packages.

*Make default pagesize configuration with a default value of 10
go to http://localhost:8081/api/products?page=1

*Implement API integration test using RestAssured and Testcontainers.
You can test a particular class, that is you can test only the controller, service or repository without loading the other classes.
To write an integration test, create an abstract integration text inside test folder
when we write an integration test,
the idea is to load all the components and make an api endpoint call and verify the response.
This is where we can use springboot @ annotation
The @springBoot annotation is used to write an integration test which will load the entire application
we can use @dataJpa to test only the repository.
for education purpose
we will write an integration test and a unit test for repository as well.
we already have a default test which is "CatalogServiceApplicationTests"
CatalogServiceApplicationTests: This tests wether our application can be started.
Instead of writing this annotation '@Import(TestcontainersConfiguration.class) @SpringBootTest' for every integration test,
Lets create a base class(AbstractIT) AbstractIntegrationTest
By default springBoot test starts at a specific port but it is advised to use a random port.
@LocalServerPort: This will bind the random port to the "port" variable.
Then we extend the AbsractIT in the CatalogServiceApplicationTests.
then we run "CatalogServiceApplicationTests".
then we create our ProductControllerTest to test only our controller.
When testing the controller always make sure our data is in a known state, like know the amount of data.
we create a test-data.sql in the test resources folder.
annotate the ProductControllerTest with @Sql and add our test-data.sql
The annotation will load the sql script before execute the method in the ProductControllerTest
    For unit test
How do we test a repository
We will test with postgres dataBase
since we are using test containers
    Get product by code api endpoint
create a findByCode in ProductRepository
    How to handle the exception if we put an invalid code/product not found
Handling an exception and throwing an exception are not the same thing.
We can create a global exception handler to handle the errors
article on global exception handling : https://www.sivalabs.in/blog/spring-boot-3-error-reporting-using-problem-details
It is advisable to add a generic handling exception even if you have a specific error handling exception.
    Testing the repository for Get product by code(unit test)
We create a test for "Get product by code" in ProductRepositoryTest
    Testing the Controller
We create a unit test for ProductController in ProductControllerTest
note: for integration test, use @SpringBootTest annotation: because it is going to load the entire application.
for unit test like repository test, use @DataJpaTest: This going to load partial component i.e only the repository.

Todo 4
How to dockerize our catalog-service application
    -Configure spring boot mavin plugin to create docker image with name steverado9/bookstore-catalog-service
If you want to build a docker image in springBoot, you dont need to create a docker file cos
Behind the scene springBoot uses Cloud mavin Buildpacks to build docker image.
go to the pom.xml of catalog-service
go to <properties> and add <dockerImageName>
then configure the springBoot mavin plugin
then open the terminal and run: ./mvnw  -pl catalog-service spring-boot:build-image -DskipTests
    -Create Dockerhub access token
create an account on dockerhub
after login in, go to personal access token
click on generate new access token
Description: DockerHubAccessToken
Permission: Read, Write
Then click generate
Copy the access token : <DOCKER_ACCESS_TOKEN>
Then we go to our code repository on github
click on settings
click on secrets and variables, then actions
In Repository secrets,
Add DOCKERHUB_USERNAME, DOCKERHUB_TOKEN
There is a github login-action call "https://github.com/docker/login-action", we use it to login into our docker account.
Then we go into our catalog-service.yml in github/workflow folder
and paste this " -name: Login to Docker Hub uses: docker/login-action@v4 with: username: ${{ vars.DOCKERHUB_USERNAME }} password: ${{ secrets.DOCKERHUB_TOKEN }}"
Then we will build docker-image and push it to dockerhub
still in our catalog-service.yml
Note: We should only do login to docker-hub and build, publish docker images when it is merged to the main branch on github.

before pushing, lets build docker image locally and see if everything is working
so in our deployment/docker-compose folder
we go to the apps.yml
now we are both running database and catalog-service in docker container
we have to connect it in our catalog-service application.yml
We overwrite the values for DB_URL, DB_USERNAME and DB_PASSWORD in the application.yml from the apps.yml
In our Task.yml file we will add configuration for apps.yml (shortcut to run it)
the run "task start" to start the catalog_db(postgres database) and catalog-service(application) containers.
You will see the two containers started and you can access the urls in the controller eg "http://localhost:8081/api/products/P110"

-Configure Dockerhub credentials as secret Github Repository
-Update Github Actions to build docker image and push it to Dockerhub